Feasible omega

Jonathan Mah, Undergraduate Researcher @ Bloom Lab, FHCRC

February 5 2019

The purpose of this R Markdown Notebook is to document the decisions used to determine feasible values of omega for use in simulating alignments to be analyzed by the REL approach towards identifying sites under positive selection, in the software package phydms.

We must first install the necessary packages:

# Install readr package to read in from given csv files
library(readr)
# Install ggplot2 package for graphics
library(ggplot2)

First we need to define the sites which are simulated as being under negative selection, moderate positive selection, and strong positive selection. We will be evaluating sites under moderate and strong positive selection together because ideally we can detect multiple levels of positive selection.

divpressure_file = '../../Analysis/Simulations/H3H_Simulation_12_50_075_15_2/divpressure_17_pos_34_mod.csv'
divpressure = read.csv(divpressure_file)
mod_selection_value = median(unique(divpressure$DivPressure))
mod_selection = divpressure[is.element(divpressure$DivPressure, mod_selection_value),]
mod_selection = mod_selection$X.Site
max_selection = divpressure[is.element(divpressure$DivPressure, 1.0),]
max_selection = max_selection$X.Site
pos_selection = append(mod_selection, max_selection)

Then, we can calculate evaluate the results at different cutoffs of posterior probability.

for (omega_min in c('075', '09')) {
  for (omega_mod in c('15', '175')) {
    for (omega_max in c('2', '5', '10')) {
      dummy_posterior_probability_file = '../../Analysis/Simulations/H3H_phydms_12_50_min_mod_max/posteriorprobabilities.csv'
      given_posterior_probability_file = sub('min', omega_min, dummy_posterior_probability_file)
      given_posterior_probability_file = sub('mod', omega_mod, given_posterior_probability_file)
      given_posterior_probability_file = sub('max', omega_max, given_posterior_probability_file)
      posterior_probability = read.csv(given_posterior_probability_file)
      cutoff_vector <- c()
      tp_vector <- c()
      tn_vector <- c()
      fp_vector <- c()
      fn_vector <- c()
      sensitivity_vector <- c()
      specificity_vector <- c()
      false_discovery_vector <- c()
      for (cutoff in seq(0, 1, 0.01)) {
        true_positive = 0
        false_positive = 0
        false_negative = 0
        true_negative = 0
        for (site in seq(1, 565, 1)) {
          site_probability = posterior_probability[is.element(posterior_probability$site, site),]$pr.positive_selection
          # Determine if site is positive or negative selection
          if (site %in% pos_selection) {
            if (site_probability > cutoff) {
              true_positive = true_positive + 1
            } else {
              # site_probability <= cutoff
              false_negative = false_negative + 1
            }
          } else {
            # Not in positive_selection
            if (site_probability > cutoff) {
              false_positive = false_positive + 1
            } else {
              # site_probability <= cutoff
              true_negative = true_negative + 1
            }
          }
        }
        cutoff_vector = append(cutoff_vector, cutoff)
        tp_vector = append(tp_vector, true_positive)
        tn_vector = append(tn_vector, true_negative)
        fp_vector = append(fp_vector, false_positive)
        fn_vector = append(fn_vector, false_negative)
        sensitivity_vector = append(sensitivity_vector, true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative))
        specificity_vector = append(specificity_vector, true_negative / (true_negative + false_positive))
        false_discovery_vector = append(false_discovery_vector, false_positive / (false_positive + true_positive))
      }
      output = sub('posteriorprobabilities', 'performancebycutoff', given_posterior_probability_file)
      df = data.frame(cutoff_vector, tp_vector, fn_vector, fp_vector, fn_vector, sensitivity_vector, specificity_vector, false_discovery_vector)
      names(df) = c('Cutoff percentage', 'True positive', 'True negative', 'False positive', 'False negative', 'Sensitivity', 'Specificity', 'False Discovery Rate')
      write.csv(df, output)
    }
  }
}

We visualize the results using an ROC curve, as well as by plotting True Positive Rate (TPR) and False Discovery Rate (FDR) versus different cutoff percentages.

omega_min = 0.75, omega_mod = 1.5, omega_max = 2

data_1 = read.csv('../../Analysis/Simulations/H3H_phydms_12_50_075_15_2/performancebycutoff.csv')
data_1$omega_min = 0.75
data_1$omega_mod = 1.5
data_1$omega_max = 2
p <- ggplot(data_1, aes(x=1 - data_1$Specificity, y=data_1$Sensitivity)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  geom_line(data=data_1, aes(x=data_1$Sensitivity, y=data_1$Sensitivity), linetype='dashed') +
  xlab('False Positive Rate') +
  ylab('True Positive Rate') + 
  ggtitle('ROC Curve')
p

p_2 <- ggplot(data_1, aes(x=data_1$Cutoff.percentage, y=data_1$Sensitivity)) +
  geom_line() +
  xlab('Cutoff percentage') +
  ylab('True Positive Rate') +
  ggtitle('True Positive Rate vs. Cutoff Percentage')
p_2

p_3 <- ggplot(data_1, aes(x=data_1$Cutoff.percentage, y=data_1$False.Discovery.Rate)) + 
  geom_line() +
  xlab('Cutoff percentage') +
  ylab('False Discovery Rate') +
  ggtitle('False Discovery Rate vs. Cutoff Percentage')
p_3

p_all

For clarification, the columns of the facet grid correspond to values of omega_max, the rows indicated by the outer labels correspond to values of omega_min, and the rows indicated by the inner labels correspond to values of omega_mod.

For the facet grid describing the rate of true positives, we would expect that as the cutoff percentage approaches one, the true positive rate should approach zero. Ideally, we have a high true positive rate for as high of a cutoff percentage as possible.

Recall that the formula for false discovery rate is given by (False positives) / (True positives + False positives), i.e., the number of false positives divided by the total number of positive signals. For the facet grid describing the false discovery rate, we observe that the false discovery rate either cuts off (because there are no positive signals), or reaches zero (because there are no false positives).

Of note, all of the ROC curves are above the y=x line, which is desirable as it suggests that for all cutoff percentages, the True positive rate is greater than the false positive rate. Ideally, we would observe a large large vertical spike near the beginning of the ROC curve, as that would indicate that there are datapoints where there is essentially no false positives.
